author: @ClydeJHatbird
text:
Just finished watching this today. Was really enjoyable. I like how they've moved that "humanity's protector" thing away from Godzilla and gave it to Kong, that was never his thing. G just goes the entire movie in irritated dad mode, only caring about resolving the plot, not who gets in his way, and I loved every moment of it. There's so much resolution in the end for the characters, monsters included. I still think the first (yeah, I'm one of those) and KotM are the best ones, but this comes in right after them.

I'd like to see a more Godzilla centric threat in a possible sequel. Give me something nutty like Biolante or Space Godzilla.

author: @Grindor-FR
text:
I'm now seeing just how divided these comments are on the movie, I thought the movie was good. But for the people who hate on it, they usually complain that it was "cheesy" or "stupid"

That's supposed to be what Godzilla is and that's what made him popular in the first place. 80% of Godzilla's movies had cheesy and frankly dumb elements.

This movie felt kinda like an old Showa Era Godzilla movie with modern day effects. I actually saw someone complain about Jia having powers and all that, they weren't HER powers. They were Mothra's. She bestowed them upon Jia to aid with her resurrection and destiny kind of stuff (which Mothra has done before in past movies, she has gifted humans.. mainly native cultures with abilities and powers)

If you want a serious godzilla movie, go watch Minus One. This movie was meant to be big dumb fun, a time where you turn your brain off and enjoy the spectacle.

author: @suryavarmakandasamy5493
text:
My take on how Legendary should do Phase 2 of Monsterverse after Godzilla vs Kong. Here's a conceptual outline for a series of Godzilla and Kong movies that subtly hint at SpaceGodzilla's existence, leading up to a climactic reveal in the final film:

*Film 1: Godzilla: Echoes of the Void*
- *Plot:* Godzilla battles a new Titan that has emerged from the depths of the ocean. Monarch discovers alien DNA within the Titan, suggesting extraterrestrial origins.
- *Hint:* Post-credits scene shows a meteorite heading towards Earth, with a faint, sinister roar echoing from within.

*Film 2: Kong: Hollow Earth Sovereign*
- *Plot:* Kong defends his dominion in the Hollow Earth against invading creatures. He discovers ancient murals depicting a battle between Godzilla's ancestors and a mysterious cosmic entity.
- *Hint:* A Monarch team studying cosmic radiation picks up unusual signals resembling the alien DNA found earlier.

*Film 3: Godzilla: Rise of the Leviathans*
- *Plot:* Godzilla faces multiple Titans rising simultaneously around the world. Monarch theorizes they are being awakened by a powerful external force.
- *Hint:* A crystalline structure is found on one of the defeated Titans, unlike anything on Earth.

*Film 4: Kong: Apex Predator*
- *Plot:* Kong encounters a new threat in the Hollow Earth, a creature that seems to be a corrupted version of Godzilla's species.
- *Hint:* Monarch uncovers a link between the creature and the meteorite, which is now closer to Earth.

*Film 5: Godzilla X Kong: Battle for the Cosmos*
- *Plot:* The final showdown. As the meteorite crashes, SpaceGodzilla emerges, threatening all life on Earth.
- *Hint:* Throughout the movie, flashbacks and Monarch's research connect the dots, revealing SpaceGodzilla's backstory and its ties to Godzilla and Kong's lineage.

This approach allows for a gradual buildup of mystery and anticipation, with each movie contributing pieces to the puzzle of SpaceGodzilla's existence, culminating in an epic confrontation that ties together the entire saga.

author: @shoelesblondlady
text: As a kid who loved Godzilla movies and Jurassic park it's been a severely disappointing series of movies. Godzilla movies were corny but I had hope they could make it interesting but it seemed like they blew their load paying Bryan Cranston to be in the first movie for 15 minutes. They seemed to try to fix that in the second but a 12 year old in need of Ritalin must have written that script and the actors were worse than old voiceover Godzilla actors. I know I lumped Jurassic park in there on a Godzilla commercial but I loved them. Jurassic world seems like they gave 4th graders the task of writing a 2 hour mom van commercial with dinosaurs. Kong puts out bangers but I just haven't enjoyed the crossover. I had hope for the last Kong vs godzilla...

author: @Soleprofit559
text: So the story go leaked â€¦ I wonâ€™t give it all away but basically scar king is trying to take over the world and mate with whatever titans he wants to mate with. Hollow earth isnâ€™t big enough anymore and he has tamed an army of Kong species to help him fight other titans trying to stop him . He also had an encounter with shimu who is actually godzillas mom and has tamed shimu to do his bidding . He may have sexually taken advantage of her so we might see a cross species between the orange monkey and Godzillas mom in the next movie who will either be a villain or the heir to Godzilla.  Also the reason soku â€œkongs sonâ€ is orange is because scar king took advantage of kongs mom before she died and scar and kongs mom had a baby . So soku is actually kongs lil half brother and scar king is the step dad of kong . In the end kong kills scar king with the help of his step brother soki . Soku gets the kill and it goes to his head and so he sees himself as the heir of kong and might cause conflict within himself in future films . Soku is at the tipping point between hero and villain so that sets up next movie . Godzilla fights his mom shimu and he wins . He doesnâ€™t kill his mom though . He actually lets her live and since they are closely related not only by blood, but by species, they see its only right that they mate and have kids so they can keep their species alive going forward while also improving their species with better traits and capabilities to protect humanity in the future . Spoiler alert for future monsterverse movie  ğŸš¨- godzilla and kong are old and the duties of protecting earth have taken a toll on there bodies . Aside from his infinity gauntlet the humans will need to make him a cane or a wheelchair and Godzilla will be slow moving and mostly live under the sea hibernating to preserve whatever energy he has left at old age which equals even less screen time for him. Godzilla and shimus son (maybe Manila) will face off against soku (kongs son/stepbro) to see who will be the new king of monsters and protector of humanity. But yet again these two will have to set aside their differences for a new villain and threat to humanity. We donâ€™t know who that villain is yet but we believe itâ€™s gonna be scar  king and shimus offspring becuase remember he might have impregnated her too. Maybe itâ€™s a Toho monster or maybe legendary will just make another monster cause they are greedy and donâ€™t want to pay Toho any more money than they have to already . Thatâ€™s why GxK is mainly a kong movie and story Because more screen time for Godzilla means they have to pay Toho more money . I see Godzilla and Kong taking a backseat completely or be absent in the next film so legendary can create their own monsters to capitalize on all the profits instead of having to pay money to the creative owners of Kong and Godzilla .

author: @eliskardaentertainment5066
text:
I honestly think this trailer ranges from pretty good to okay in certain moments.

I love how Godzilla now has a new magenta or rose-colored atomic breath and some new dorsal spikes to go along with them, but at the same time, his lower half does seem a bit off. Sure it looks better than that one recent toy leak we got last month, but Iâ€™m worried that it might look too slim for me, I really miss having Godzillaâ€™s lower half being big and bulky like his upper half like in previous Monsterverse movies. Overall, itâ€™s still a cool and interesting design for the G-Man.

Also, I do think Skar King is going to be a pretty effective villain in the Monsterverse along Shimu and I do like how Kong is now have his own baby son to raise once Skar King and Shimu are finally defeated, That â€œSon Of Kongâ€ movie is honestly now going to be something to look forward to seeing as how we now have a proper explanation as to why thereâ€™s a baby kong now.

As for Kong having a metal arm, I think itâ€™s something he might need to survive the war against Skar King and Shimu alongside his axe or heâ€™s going to receive a severe injury to his arm will cause him to need that mechanical upgrade.

The CGI looks pretty good for the most part, but it could definitely use some improvements in the future.

Overall, I think this is a pretty decent trailer for Godzilla X Kong: The New Empire, Iâ€™ll give it a 7/10!

author: @TriangleThe13thPrime
text:
The trailer for "Godzilla X Kong: The New Empire" stands as a cinematic marvel, not merely a glimpse into an impending blockbuster, but a transformative experience that transcends the boundaries of traditional film promotion. The visual symphony begins with a crescendo of monstrous roars and titanic clashes, setting the stage for a colossal battle between two iconic behemoths, Godzilla and Kong. The CGI mastery and cinematography create a spectacle that, while awe-inspiring, is just the tip of the emotional iceberg that this trailer unveils.

As the camera sweeps over urban landscapes torn asunder and titans locked in epic combat, a surprising undercurrent of emotional depth emerges. The trailer defies expectations, revealing not just the physical might of these legendary creatures but also their vulnerabilities and the emotional stakes of their conflict. Moments of quiet introspection and connection between the colossal combatants inject a humanizing element into the narrative, transforming the trailer into a tale of not just monsters, but of heroes grappling with their own existential challenges.

The soundtrack, carefully curated to complement the visual narrative, weaves a tapestry of emotions. From the thunderous beats that accompany the intense action sequences to the haunting melodies that underscore the quieter, more reflective moments, the music becomes a visceral component of the storytelling. Each note resonates with the audience, eliciting a range of feelings from adrenaline-pumping excitement to introspective contemplation.

As the trailer unfolds, it becomes evident that the clash between Godzilla and Kong serves as a metaphor for the internal struggles that define the human experience. The destructive force unleashed upon the cityscape becomes an allegory for life's challenges, and the unexpected alliances formed amidst the chaos reflect the potential for collaboration and unity even in the face of adversity. The symbolism embedded in the trailer transforms what could have been a mere monster movie into a parable of hope, resilience, and the indomitable human spirit.

On a personal level, the trailer's messages resonate with a profound intensity, leaving an imprint on the soul. The unexpected emotional journey, seamlessly interwoven with the grandiosity of the monster clashes, transcends the boundaries of typical film marketing. It becomes a catalyst for introspection, prompting reflection on one's own life and the battles faced on a day-to-day basis.

In the weeks following the trailer's release, its impact lingers, morphing into a source of inspiration during moments of self-doubt or adversity. The positive messages of collaboration, resilience, and the capacity for growth become guiding principles, shaping not only the anticipation for the full movie but also influencing personal decisions and interactions.

The trailer for "Godzilla X Kong: The New Empire" becomes a cinematic mentor, offering life lessons in unexpected places. Its ability to merge spectacle with substance transforms it into a beacon of positivity, radiating messages of hope and empowerment. As I eagerly await the full movie, I find myself carrying the trailer's lessons into various aspects of my life, embracing challenges with a newfound courage and approaching collaborations with a sense of unity and purpose.

In conclusion, the "Godzilla X Kong: The New Empire" trailer transcends its role as a mere promotional tool. It emerges as a cinematic masterpiece, a transformative experience that leaves an indelible mark on the viewer. The marriage of visual grandeur with emotional depth, coupled with positive and inspirational messages, elevates the trailer beyond the realm of traditional blockbuster marketing. It becomes a journey of self-discovery, fostering personal growth and imparting invaluable lessons that resonate long after the final frame fades to black.

Move into GvsK and they show kong was basically a joke in hong kong when Godzilla had enough of kongs playtime and he destroyed him no problem. then they show a power displayed by mechagodzilla that could actually take godzilla down. Now what we are seeing in GxK the new empire, is what i believe to be the same power and godzilla is feeding on it. I belive godzilla will be even more powerful now but that means scar king is going to be a serious probelm because a full powered godzill plus kong have to take him down. Just a theory though obviously. Anyone feel the same?

author: @natewoodburn9820
text:
I have a theory of why godzilla is more 'lanky' and keeps in line with what godzilla has done from his previous fights.

against muto prime, his dorsal plates were destroyed, so he evolved to have better plates the counter the muto primes scream.

against King ghidorah, he got his thermonuclear upgrade from the nuke and mother's sacrifice.

and now he has evolved from his fight against mecha-godzilla who had RED dorsal plates and very 'lanky' arms and legs.

I think godzilla has evolved to counter any new mecha-godzilla's and any new threats such as this new 'Scar King'.

plus red and blue mixed together is a magenta/pink colour.
